ion, as well as produce new tools for digital surveillance-which can jeopardize privacy and civil liberties.Cybercrime brings together leading experts in law, criminal justice, and security studies to describe crime prevention and security protection in the electronic age. Ranging from new government requirements that facilitate spying to new methods of digital proof, the book is essential to understand how criminal law-and even crime itself-have been transformed in our networked world.Contributors: Jack M. Balkin, Susan W. Brenner, Daniel E. Geer, Jr., James Grimmelmann, Emily Hancock, Beryl A. Howell, Curtis E.A. Karnow, Eddan Katz, Orin S. Kerr, Nimrod Kozlovski, Helen Nissenbaum, Kim A. Taipale, Lee Tien, Shlomit Wagman, and Tal Zarsky.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComputer crimeszUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aComputer securityzUnited StatesxEvaluation. 0aInternetxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh  aCybercrime.  aage.  abrings.  acrime.  acriminal.  adescribe.  aelectronic.  aexperts.  ajustice.  alaw.  aleading.  aprevention.  aprotection.  asecurity.  astudies.  atogether.1 aBalkin, Jack M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalkin, Jack M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrenner, Susan W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeer, Daniel E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimmelmann, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHancock, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowell, Beryl A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarnow, Curtis E. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel